00:00.880 --> 00:12.340
The tape is rolling, so it's all on record now. Alright. And I obviously have
your biography, but I'll have to ask some things for the fans. Okay, tell us a

00:12.340 --> 00:24.160
little bit how you grew up and what might have influenced you to write science
fiction. Well, I grew up in a suburb of Cleveland called Fairview Park and I

00:24.160 --> 00:34.040
think I was influenced to write science fiction by the fact that when I was a
kid, I'd go into the public library once or twice a week. And they had a very

00:34.040 --> 00:44.240
small children's section. And it wasn't long before I'd devoured, you know, all
the Hardy Boys and the Tom Swifts. And I went to the librarian and said, hey,

00:44.300 --> 00:51.780
look, let me into the older section, okay, because there's nothing left here for
me to read. And she took me over to this row of books that had rockets on their

00:51.780 --> 01:00.820
spines and said, have you read any of these? I said, no. What is it? She said,
it's called science fiction. Why don't you give it a try? and that pretty much

01:00.820 --> 01:12.180
started a lifelong love affair with science fiction right there in six months
had cleaned out that library but by then i was a newspaper carrier and was

01:12.180 --> 01:25.220
making enough money every week to go out and buy four or five paperbacks those
were the days and you know it just never stopped got into college still reading

01:25.220 --> 01:34.460
five ten science fiction paperbacks a week and realized my tastes, I think,
matured a little, and I started saying, my God, I could write better than this.

01:35.620 --> 01:47.400
I said that so often that one of my roommates said, Kevin, I'd have put up or
shut up, and I started writing junior, senior year of college. I discovered it

01:47.400 --> 02:00.600
was a lot harder than I had thought, but by, I think it was 1973, I'd I made my
first short story sale to Analog and followed it up a couple of years later with

02:00.600 --> 02:05.200
another and decided, well, you know, this should sort of be working for a
living.

02:09.300 --> 02:20.260
Okay, you lived in the Orient, different places in the Orient for some time, and
your major was Chinese studies. How did you get interested in Chinese studies

02:20.260 --> 02:25.180
and in the Orient, and has that influenced your science fiction in any way?

02:28.100 --> 02:39.720
Well, to start with, I wound up in the Orient because my father joined the Peace
Corps in 1966 and trucked the entire family off to Seoul, Korea, well, I was

02:39.720 --> 02:49.280
there for two years. The rest of the family was there for four. This is my
junior and senior year in high school. I went to a small missionary school in

02:49.280 --> 03:03.800
Seoul, Korea, Seoul Foreign School. Because it was Peace Corps, we were sort of
under orders to avoid the American community. We all got extensive language

03:03.800 --> 03:04.360
training.

03:07.220 --> 03:23.300
We lived in the Korean community. After two years of daily language lessons and
all, I'd become reasonably fluent in Korean. And when I graduated high school, I

03:23.300 --> 03:34.620
had this dream that I would become the world's foremost American authority on
Korea. So when I applied to colleges, I applied to universities that had good,

03:34.780 --> 03:47.860
solid Korean studies programs. Yale was one of them. They accepted me. And I,
you know, accepted them joyfully. Came back from Seoul to New Haven,

03:48.000 --> 03:58.340
Connecticut. and discovered that over the summer they'd killed their entire
Korean studies program, which sort of left me out on a limb. I'd cast around for

03:58.340 --> 04:08.160
the nearest related subject, and that was Chinese studies. I figured I could,
since most of Korean history is actually written in Chinese rather than in

04:08.160 --> 04:18.040
Korean, I figured, well, OK, I'll learn Chinese now. And spent four years
discovering that I was not cut out to be an academic,

04:21.360 --> 04:30.940
Did this experience in the Orient and in studying other cultures, does that have
any influence as far as your writing something like alien cultures or what it's

04:30.940 --> 04:43.180
like to be among aliens? Very much. It's hit me on a couple of different levels.
One is this is more true, I think, of Americans who live in Asia than those who

04:43.180 --> 04:53.820
live in Europe or South America because in Asia, you're very conscious of the
fact that you're a foreigner. I mean, you're racially different. You do not have

04:53.820 --> 05:05.260
black hair and dark brown eyes. Everywhere you walk, people look at you.
Especially in some of the more rural areas of the country like Korea, which the

05:05.260 --> 05:17.180
last time they saw an American was during the war, 20 years ago, 20 years before
I was there. they are unabashed in their curiosity and it really engenders the

05:17.180 --> 05:29.840
self-consciousness in the American to constantly be stared at to have people
touching to see if you feel the same as a Korean does so I think that's

05:29.840 --> 05:43.540
affecting my science fiction writing in how a person feels when he's among
aliens at the same time Asian languages and cultures are significantly different

05:43.540 --> 05:56.260
from Western cultures in terms of the way they view almost everything. And
although it's not really an alien psychology, it's sufficiently different that

05:56.260 --> 06:10.180
it gives me sort of an insight into how a sentient being from Rigel or whatever
could view things differently, could take a really far-out perspective on

06:10.180 --> 06:22.280
something we just take for granted. When you first started writing science
fiction and then other fiction, you wrote short stories. How long did you write

06:22.280 --> 06:29.500
short stories before you then moved to the novel form, and how did you make that
transition? Oh, it seems like forever.

06:32.120 --> 06:48.400
Oh I think I wrote shorts heavily for a good four years. I started really
writing in earnest seriously in the summer of 72 after I graduated from college

06:48.400 --> 07:02.340
and that was I was back at Neysha at that time. I was teaching. I had a lot of
free time. And I turned out a lot of stories in 72, 73, came back to the States

07:02.340 --> 07:18.500
in 74, and I made a couple fails. I thought I could do better. Kept at it. And I
guess between 72 and 76, I probably wrote close to 100 short stories. And I

07:18.500 --> 07:31.580
was... By 75, 76, I was selling at a respectable clip I began to realize that on
the one hand I mean from a purely mercenary point of view you can't make a

07:31.580 --> 07:41.820
living writing short stories at least not science fiction short stories there
are markets out there that want short stories that need a lot of them but they

07:41.820 --> 07:54.440
don't pay enough and so I started for financial reasons looking at the novel
probably as early as late 74 early 75 but I was scared for a long time it

07:54.440 --> 08:06.820
terrified me to think of tackling a novel a novel is big you know a short story
you go 5,000 words and you say end and that's it 20 pages all nice and neat you

08:06.820 --> 08:19.160
can retype 20 pages in an afternoon you can write the whole thing in a week if
you really push yourself but a novel I mean that's Mount Everest so I put off

08:19.160 --> 08:34.260
writing the novel until I think it was 75, 76 before I even started admitting,
hey, it's time to get going on this. And even then I dawdled for more.

08:37.480 --> 08:48.700
Finally people were sensing my reluctance to tackle this and a lot of my friends
started giving me trouble. Hey, you know, come on, it's time, you should do it.

08:49.560 --> 08:57.100
So I did. Wrote Bandersnatch, sold it to Benson Books, and been writing novels
other since.

09:00.040 --> 09:10.600
Bandersnatch was written in first person, which is usually kind of a hard way to
write. How did you decide to do it that way? Well, first person is a real hard

09:10.600 --> 09:17.380
way to write well, but it's a very easy way in which to write.

09:20.800 --> 09:30.360
Bandersnatch might possibly have been a better book had it been written in third
person but first person just seemed so natural I'd written, a lot of the stories

09:30.360 --> 09:40.060
I'd written in first person and I just felt that I could have a better control
of my material if I tried it in first person I don't think it was completely

09:40.060 --> 09:52.580
successful One of your talents which really shows through in Bandersnatch is the
use of slang and invented language. Do you work hard on this, or does this come

09:52.580 --> 10:05.700
naturally? Bandersnatch, well, no, it does not come naturally. Some words, some
terms come very easily. When you're working on a 300-page manuscript and you've

10:05.700 --> 10:21.540
read it 82 times, certain words just sort of rise up out of the text at you. But
Bandersnatch was a very deliberate attempt to put the swine in there. I went to,

10:21.640 --> 10:35.500
I think it was the second or third draft, and I realized this lacked a
sufficient feel of the future. It just felt much too 1970-ish. And one of the

10:35.500 --> 10:47.220
reasons was the way that people were talking to each other. So I said, OK, look,
let's invent a future slime. It's not an original concept. Lots of people have

10:47.220 --> 11:00.540
done it. Lots of people have done it a lot better. But I sat down, and I had
this social subgroup. And I figured, OK, what kind of slanguage are these people

11:00.540 --> 11:11.040
going to develop? What are they going to have slang words for? We're talking
outlaws here. they're going to have words for police and each other and criminal

11:11.040 --> 11:26.980
acts, and I tried to almost extrapolate some of the words from the way they are
today. Other words I tried to take off of their origin, others sort of

11:26.980 --> 11:38.440
acronymized. EDRA III, the locale where much of the book takes place, came from
the federal dependence resettlement area, which FDRA, and pretty soon it's EDRA.

11:41.920 --> 11:50.440
LEAPERS, one of the flying terms for police, came from the law enforcement
agency personnel, and things like that.

11:53.300 --> 12:04.920
This book seemed almost angry Bandersnatch and then the other people where you
was this anything heavily psychological about this or is this the way it came

12:04.920 --> 12:18.780
out well I think it came out that way for two reasons first the pace at which I
wrote it it took a long time to write but I wrote almost entirely on weekends

12:18.780 --> 12:32.300
and I try and knock took off 10 pages a day every weekend. When you write at
that speed, I think emotions just come more naturally to the surface. Also the

12:32.300 --> 12:41.820
characters in there are, for the most part, very angry characters. There's
societies, outcasts, exiled to this artificial peninsula up there in Lake Erie,

12:41.900 --> 12:55.400
off of Ashtabula. I think at the time I felt that these people would be
naturally bitter, angry, resemble types that loses. And loses either tend to be

12:55.400 --> 12:57.020
totally innocuous or angry.

13:00.760 --> 13:12.160
One of the characters, Baby Bear, was a real cuddly animal sidekick, which you
seem to have in other books as well. Do you particularly like animals, and is

13:12.160 --> 13:14.440
there anything that particularly inspired him?

13:17.920 --> 13:36.040
I inspired Baby Bear. Baby Bear actually came about almost entirely by accident.
