13:55.720 --> 14:01.640
and I hadn't had any wild animals in there. They were really big enough for him.

14:04.720 --> 14:18.620
All of a sudden, off the page came this monstrous, bear-like animal that almost
loomed up before him and started attacking him. Well, he won, and there I was

14:18.620 --> 14:30.580
with a dead bear on the ground. Somehow my fingers kept going, and there was a
sound from the distance, and it was the cub. The next thing I knew, he had a

14:30.580 --> 14:51.180
sidekick, as you put it. That was just accidental, really. I think it worked. I
think, from a reader's interest point of view, I think it helps when the

14:51.180 --> 14:53.720
protagonist has a sidekick of some sort.

14:56.920 --> 15:10.440
When you're writing science fiction, well, you know, why not give the hero an
alien sidekick, Sam in the McGill Feighan series? I think it lets you do a little

15:10.440 --> 15:25.580
exploring into alien psychology and at the same time, it lets you keep making
sort of mirror-like observations of human culture. So I find it fun and useful

15:25.580 --> 15:36.700
and it seems to work. Mayflies then appeared and I noticed that it's coming out
in a second edition with a different cover and everything. That must be

15:36.700 --> 15:46.820
gratifying. There is. There are, of course, a lot of generationship ideas in
science fiction, but this was the first one I'd read that was from the

15:46.820 --> 15:55.820
computer's point of view. I'm sure I can't hear you. Okay. My engineer cautioned
to me I should talk less loudly so I'll tell him to screw it.

15:59.060 --> 16:07.420
Mayflies was basically, well, I'd read a lot of life ship or Generationship
science fiction stories and books, of course, there's a lot of them, but this

16:07.420 --> 16:21.020
was the first one I had read from the computer's point of view. Yeah. Was that
the intent, to do that from the computer's point of view, or a man who, well, a

16:21.020 --> 16:26.640
disembodied brain, basically? Mayfly started out as...

16:28.840 --> 16:41.580
Actually, it was a workshop exercise. I was, at the time, in a workshop here in
New Haven. And we had to do a, oh, I forget, a two-paragraph description of

16:41.580 --> 16:54.700
someone. And I described this character, Metaclura, who took more than the two
paragraphs to describe. He ran on for about a page, and all of a sudden, he

16:54.700 --> 17:04.620
died. And I took it into the workshop, and people said, well, yes, those are
nice paragraphs and very good description, but, boy, what have you done here?

17:04.760 --> 17:12.860
You know, you've created a character and then killed him. What a waste. I got
angry and said, well, you know, maybe I've killed him, but it's not a waste. But

17:12.860 --> 17:21.960
I can make something of him. And they said, we dare you. And pretty soon,
Mayflies is underway with me trying to prove you could write a book about a

17:21.960 --> 17:32.340
protagonist who died on page one. and have that protagonist a very vital part of
the entire story rather than just a haunting memory. The only way to do that

17:32.340 --> 17:43.260
was, of course, to somehow keep him alive. One thing led to another, and the
next thing I knew, Metaclura was a central computer on The Good Shit Madflower.

17:45.720 --> 17:56.660
Do those kinds of workshops help one write science fiction either to get started
or to discuss pros and kinds of stories? I think they can be very useful.

17:59.660 --> 18:10.940
It's really hard to find someone who can read and criticize science fiction
effectively. The concepts of science fiction are so different from the concepts

18:10.940 --> 18:24.920
of the mystery genre or the romance genre, whatever. and also as any if any
writer can tell you good friends who aren't writers and close relatives and like

18:24.920 --> 18:36.380
that when they read your stuff there's an implicit bias in the way they read it
they like you you're their friend their spouse their you know first cousin once

18:36.380 --> 18:46.880
removed whatever but they like you and it influences the way they read your work
it influences the way they comment on your work to you And you don't get honest

18:46.880 --> 18:59.060
feedback. You get rose-colored feedback, which is really flattering to the ego,
but it doesn't help you sell. When you go into a workshop, here are people who

18:59.060 --> 19:09.760
maybe they know you, maybe they don't, maybe they like you, maybe they don't.
But they know writing. They know science fiction in this particular instance.

19:09.760 --> 19:18.760
And they can say, okay, look, you made a nice start of the story, but it doesn't
work because of this, that, and the other. And these are things that probably

19:18.760 --> 19:25.620
your friends and relatives wouldn't see to begin with. And if they did, they'd
downplay it. They'd say, well, this is a little weak here, but don't worry about

19:25.620 --> 19:41.220
it. It's a great story. We love you. You can't really become a selling writer
with that sort of critical feedback. It doesn't help. And that, I think, is

19:41.220 --> 19:49.860
where workshops can be very useful. They can also be destructive when all the
egos are on parade and people start slashing each other up just for the sheer

19:49.860 --> 20:03.520
joy of cutting and watching somebody else ride. In that case, the workshop is
destructive and not worth it. Okay, I'm glad I asked that. Back to Mayflies. Was

20:03.520 --> 20:17.700
Mayflies your title? My original title for Mayflies was Mayflies and Other
Spaced Spirits, which if you look it up in books and print is still the official

20:17.700 --> 20:28.420
title. But the sales department at Berkeley thought that this was a little,
sounded too much like an anthology, they said. And anthologies weren't selling.

20:31.980 --> 20:40.260
there was a market for novels but simply not for collections of short stories
and they said look let's cut the rest of the title cut it back to one word short

20:40.260 --> 20:51.640
punchy no confusion over what the book is and as every writer knows the writer
really doesn't have much choice and the sales department says change the title

20:53.460 --> 21:03.500
so I went along with it and they washed it it I haven't yet had a title accepted
by a sales department. I've written six, published six books, and the sales

21:03.500 --> 21:13.640
department has changed the title on every one of them. Okay, that brings up,
well, not the next book, but the next one to talk about, because I want to do

21:13.640 --> 21:24.080
the other three together, but War of Omission, what was its original title? The
original title of War of Omission was Lithian Lament, which is now the title of

21:24.080 --> 21:35.320
one of the subsections. I thought that was really artsy evocative nice in the
sales department nah

21:38.120 --> 21:47.320
in decisions like this the sales department always has the final facts I
remember reading in Locus that there was a forthcoming book by that title and I

21:47.320 --> 21:58.980
wondered what happened to it yeah that's where it went ok this book again it's
not, this isn't first person but it's multiple viewpoints which I understand is

21:58.980 --> 22:14.520
just about as hard to write viewpoints of several different people. Yeah. I was
trying something and what I tried to do in there was sort of inspired by one of

22:14.520 --> 22:24.280
those masterpiece theater PBS shows. At this point, I'm embarrassed to say I
can't remember the play or the characters or the actors or anything.

22:28.100 --> 22:37.800
But the first episode was told entirely from one person's point of view and the
second from the point of view of someone else who was also a minor character in

22:37.800 --> 22:48.760
that first episode. So it went through the series. And I said, geez, it could be
fun to try this. So I very deliberately picked out, I think, eight major

22:48.760 --> 23:01.360
characters in there, gave each of them one section of the book to be the
protagonist in that section, and had them appear elsewhere as minor characters

23:01.360 --> 23:12.300
until the end is supposed to rotate back and forth through all eight different
heads. I was trying to view this cataclysm

23:12.300 --> 23:23.280
from as many different viewpoints as I could while still maintaining storyline
continuity. Did it work? Yeah, I thought it was great. It was very interesting.

23:23.280 --> 23:36.780
I like that particular approach myself, and I just don't see it very often.
Okay, as in Bandersnatch, the society that you portray is pretty much strangled

23:36.780 --> 23:52.460
by a burgeoning bureaucracy. Is this a personal view? Do you fear that? Yes, it
is. I really see it happening not only here but pretty much everywhere where

23:52.460 --> 24:05.700
governments have been in power for any length of time. I think it's the nature
of the beast, a bureaucracy of any sort, whether it's governmental, corporate,

24:06.020 --> 24:22.280
academic. it achieves a goal beyond its stated purpose or it acquires a new goal
in that that goal is to survive to perpetuate itself to expand to get fat and

24:22.280 --> 24:32.760
strong and secure it goes all the way back to Parkinson's Law work expands until
the time available and when it has you hire two assistants

24:35.340 --> 24:43.240
I think this is an inevitable trend in any bureaucracy whether it's western
style capitalism

24:46.560 --> 24:57.800
Maoist communism one of Mao's big campaigns was against bureaucracy he was
constantly railing against the way that no matter what he said no matter what he

24:57.800 --> 25:08.800
did the bureaucracy kept growing It kept issuing new regulations and new rules,
and here he was, the most powerful man in China, and he couldn't affect the

25:08.800 --> 25:13.520
bureaucracy. So, yeah, that's a very personal point with me.

